value: Jar with wooden core, inlaid with mother of pearl. Choson Dynasty. This tall jar of maebyong shape has a wide straight neck and a broad shoulder, from which it narrows towards the flaring foot; it has a low footring. The upper part of the body is divided by horizontal lines into three zones, each decorated with a lotus scroll and the lower two also with birds in flight; the motifs are all cut from mother-of-pearl and inlaid into a dark brownish-red lacquer, which has turned almost black, flaked away in places, and lost part of the inlay.

summary_title: Korean Art from the Gompertz and Other Collections in the Fitzwilliam Museum, A Complete Catalogue
